<font color="#FF0000">POLITICS OF MONEY</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jun  1  0:13:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Andy,<br><br>
We WERE there BIG and PUSHING in the 60's and 70's with more fire power than was seen in many places in WW2. We also provided jobs for the civilian population, and built an infrastructure to support much of that population. We helped orphanages and schools, and provided more outreach medical attention in the bush than we currently provide our own homeless citizens.<br><br>
...and it all went down the drain.<br><br>
I feel that to use the logic that infusing Vietnam now with money and infrastructure will bring democracy because they will trade communism in exchange for this new stuff is like trying to reform bankrobbers by letting them rob banks with impunity. It will not work. In the end, they will create a <br>
facade of joyous peace and goodwill, and will continue to<br>
pull out fingernails with visegrips in the back room. All dictatorships behave like that, always. This new policy is  far from reality and as lame as Macnamara's graduated response folly of the Vietnam War.<br><br>
I feel that our civilian government has once again lost its marbles to yuppie think tank experts who are no more in touch with reality than Adolph Hitler in his last days in his bunker in Berlin. Furthermore, since large profits are a reality from ventures there, the push from the droolers in business will move it all over the top.<br><br>
At least this time we won't get 50,000+ blown away. I bothers me that we will dishonor them with this &quot;new age&quot; politics.<br><br>
Art
